In [17]:
# converting the categorical values of "diagnosis" column from B and M to 0 and 1 respectively.

mapping = {'B': 0, 'M': 1}

data.diagnosis = data.diagnosis.map(mapping)

The above code converts the categorical values in the diagnosis column from B and M to numerical values, specifically 0 and 1, respectively. This type of encoding is often performed when you want to use categorical data in machine learning algorithms that require numerical input.

After running this code, the diagnosis column in the DataFrame will contain 0 for Benign cases and 1 for Malignant cases, which can be used as target labels for classification tasks.

In [19]:
# Splitting the dataset into training and testing sets
# xtrain: Features for training data
# xtest: Features for testing data
# ytrain: Target labels for training data
# ytest: Target labels for testing data
# test_size: Specifies the proportion of data to allocate to the testing set (25% in this case)
# random_state: Sets a seed for randomization to ensure reproducibility of results

xtrain, xtest, ytrain, ytest = train_test_split(x, y, test_size = 0.25, random_state = 0)
In [20]:
# Perform Min-Max scaling on the training and testing data
# min_max_xtrain: Scaled training data using Min-Max scaling
# min_max_xtest: Scaled testing data using Min-Max scaling
# min_max_scaler: Min-Max scaler object used for scaling
# xtrain: Original training data
# xtest: Original testing data

min_max_xtrain  = min_max_scaler.fit_transform(xtrain)
min_max_xtest  = min_max_scaler.fit_transform(xtest)
In [21]:

# Define classifiers

classifiers = {
    "Logistic Regression"   : LogisticRegression(),
    "Random Forest"         : RandomForestClassifier(),
    "Support Vector Machine": SVC(),
    "Decision Tree"         : DecisionTreeClassifier(),
    "Gradient Boosting"     : GradientBoostingClassifier(),
    "K-Nearest Neighbors"   : KNeighborsClassifier()
}

In the above code.

  • We define a Python dictionary named classifiers that stores various machine learning classifiers as key-value pairs.
  • Each key represents the name of a classifier (e.g., "Logistic Regression," "Random Forest," etc.).
  • The corresponding value for each key is an instance of the respective classifier class (e.g., LogisticRegression(), RandomForestClassifier(), etc.).
  • This dictionary is used to store and organize different machine learning models, making it convenient for experimentation and comparison of various algorithms in a machine learning workflow.
In [24]:
# Initialize lists to store metric scores for scaled data through MinMaxScaler.
accuracy_scores_mm  = []
precision_scores_mm = []
recall_scores_mm    = []
f1_scores_mm        = []

In this code:¶

  • We are initializing empty lists to store metric scores (e.g., accuracy, precision, recall, F1 score) for data that has been scaled using Min-Max Scaling (MinMaxScaler).
  • Each list is associated with a specific metric (e.g., accuracy_scores_mm for accuracy scores).
  • These lists will be populated with metric scores during the evaluation of machine learning models trained on Min-Max scaled data. This allows for the storage and analysis of model performance results.
In [25]:
# Train and evaluate machine learning classifiers
# Iterate through each classifier in the 'classifiers' dictionary

for name, clf in classifiers.items():
    
    # Display the classifier's name
    print(f"Training {name}...")
    
    # Train the classifier using Min-Max scaled training data
    clf.fit(min_max_xtrain, ytrain)
    
    # Predict the target labels using the classifier on Min-Max scaled testing data
    y_pred = clf.predict(min_max_xtest)
    
    # Calculate and display evaluation metrics (Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1-Score)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(ytest, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(ytest, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(ytest, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(ytest, y_pred)
    
    # Append the computed metric scores to their respective lists
    accuracy_scores_mm.append(accuracy)
    precision_scores_mm.append(precision)
    recall_scores_mm.append(recall)
    f1_scores_mm.append(f1)
    
    # Display the computed metric scores
    print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}")
    print(f"Precision: {precision:.2f}")
    print(f"Recall: {recall:.2f}")
    print(f"F1-Score: {f1:.2f}")
    
    # Generate and display a classification report
    report = classification_report(ytest, y_pred)
    print("Classification Report:\n", report)
    print("-" * 100)

In this code:¶

  • A dictionary named grid_search_models is created to associate machine learning models with their respective hyperparameter grids for use in grid search.
  • Each model is represented as a key in the dictionary, and its value is a tuple containing: The model instance created using the constructor (e.g., LogisticRegression(), RandomForestClassifier()).
  • A dictionary specifying the hyperparameter grid for that model. The hyperparameters and their potential values are defined within this dictionary.
  • This dictionary is structured to facilitate hyperparameter tuning (grid search) for each machine learning model, allowing you to systematically explore different hyperparameter combinations when fitting models to your data.
In [34]:
training_accuracy_GridSearch = []
testing_accuracy_GridSearch  = []

for model_name, (model, param_grid) in grid_search_models.items():
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(model, param_grid, cv=5, n_jobs=-1)
    grid_search.fit(min_max_xtrain, ytrain)
    
    print(f"\nResults for {model_name}: using the Scaled Data through MinMaxScaler Data\n")
    print("Best Parameters:", grid_search.best_params_)
    print("Best Training Accuracy:", grid_search.best_score_)
    training_accuracy_GridSearch.append(grid_search.best_score_)
    
    test_accuracy = grid_search.score(min_max_xtest, ytest)
    testing_accuracy_GridSearch.append(test_accuracy)
    print("Test Accuracy:", test_accuracy)
    print('*' * 100)

  • For each model, a GridSearchCV instance is created, which performs hyperparameter tuning using 5-fold cross-validation (cv=5) and parallelizes the process (n_jobs=-1).
  • The grid search is fit to the Min-Max scaled training data (min_max_xtrain) to find the best hyperparameters for each model.
  • The results, including the best hyperparameters, best training accuracy, and test accuracy, are printed and stored in separate lists.
  • A separator made of asterisks is printed to separate the results for each model for clarity.

This code allows you to systematically tune hyperparameters for each model and evaluate their performance on the test data using Min-Max scaled features.

Comparative Analysis Report¶

The detailed comparative analysis of the six classifiers based on their performance with both MinMaxScaler and StandardScaler. The analysis highlights that StandardScaler performed better in terms of accuracy, with Logistic Regression achieving the highest accuracy for MinMaxScaler and Gradient Boosting for StandardScaler.

Dataset Description:¶

The dataset used for this analysis contains a set of features used to predict a binary target variable (diagnosis), making it a classification problem.

Data Preprocessing:¶

The dataset underwent preprocessing, including encoding categorical variables (mapping 'B' to 0 and 'M' to 1) and scaling features using both MinMaxScaler and StandardScaler. The data was split into training and testing sets.

Evaluation Metrics:¶

Four evaluation metrics were used to assess classifier performance: Accuracy, Precision, Recall, and F1-Score. These metrics provide a comprehensive view of classifier performance.

Classifier Comparison:¶

MinMax Scaled Data:¶

  1. Logistic Regression:

    • Achieved the highest accuracy of 0.94 among MinMaxScaled classifiers.

    • Balanced Precision and a wonderfull Recall score`, indicating good overall performance.

    • F1-Score of 0.92 reflects a harmonious balance between precision and recall.

  1. Random Forest:

    • Achieved an accuracy of 0.90, demonstrating strong performance.

    • High precision (0.794) and recall (1.0) scores contribute to a high F1-Score of 0.92.

  1. Support Vector Machine (SVM):

    • Achieved an accuracy of 0.91, performing well.

    • Balanced precision and recall scores resulted in an F1-Score of 0.89.

  2. Decision Tree:

    • Achieved the lowest accuracy of 0.77 among MinMaxScaled classifiers.

    • While precision (0.72) and recall (0.98) scores are relatively balanced, there is room for improvement in overall accuracy.

StandardScaler Scaled Data:¶

  1. Logistic Regression:

    • Achieved a high accuracy of 0.958, surpassing its performance with MinMaxScaler.

    • Balanced precision and recall scores resulted in an F1-Score of 0.944.

  1. Random Forest:

    • Achieved an accuracy of 0.951, indicating strong performance with StandardScaler.

    • High precision (0.911) and recall (0.962) scores contribute to a high F1-Score of 0.958.

  1. Support Vector Machine (SVM):

    • Achieved an accuracy of 0.965, performing similarly to Random Forest.

    • Balanced precision and recall scores resulted in an F1-Score of 0.952.

  1. Decision Tree:

    • Achieved the lowest accuracy of 0.895 among StandardScaler scaled classifiers.

    • Precision (0.797) and recall (0.895) scores are relatively balanced, but there is room for improvement in overall accuracy.

  1. Gradient Boosting:

    • Achieved the highest accuracy of 0.972 among StandardScaler scaled classifiers.

    • High precision (0.930) and recall (1.00) scores resulted in an F1-Score of 0.964, demonstrating outstanding performance.

Hyperparameter Tuning with GridSearchCV:¶

GridSearchCV was applied to tune the hyperparameters of the six classifiers: Logistic Regression, Random Forest, Support Vector Machine (SVM), Decision Tree, Gradient Boosting, and K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN). The goal was to find the best combination of hyperparameters that would result in improved training and testing accuracies.

Results After Hyperparameter Tuning:¶

Training Accuracies:¶

  1. Logistic Regression:

    Achieved an impressive training accuracy of 0.983 after hyperparameter tuning.

  1. Random Forest:

    Training accuracy improved significantly and achieved 0.96.

  1. Support Vector Machine (SVM):

    Achieved a training accuracy of 0.98, matching Logistic Regression as the highest.

Testing Accuracies:¶

  1. Decision Tree:

    Achieved a testing accuracy of 0.972 after hyperparameter tuning.

  1. Gradient Boosting:

    Achieved a testing accuracy of 0.980, matching SVM as the highest.

  1. K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN):

    The lowest testing accuracy after hyperparameter tuning is achieved is 0.944 the K-Nearest Neighbors.

Feature Importance:¶

The most important features for both the StandardScaler as well as the MinMaxScaler are perimeter_worst, concave_points_worst, radius_worst, area_worst, and concave_points_mean. These are those distinctive features which really affects the classification of a cell being Benign or Malignant.

Conclusion:¶

  • StandardScaler consistently outperformed MinMaxScaler for all classifiers, with higher accuracy values.
  • Among MinMaxScaled classifiers, Logistic Regression achieved the highest accuracy, while Decision Tree had the lowest accuracy.
  • Among StandardScaler scaled classifiers, Gradient Boosting achieved the highest accuracy, while Decision Tree had the lowest accuracy.
  • Gradient Boosting with StandardScaler scaling stood out as the best-performing classifier with an accuracy of 0.972 and a well-balanced F1-Score.
  • The choice of scaling method and classifier should be made based on the specific requirements and trade-offs in precision, recall, and F1-Score for the given classification problem.
  • Hyperparameter tuning using GridSearchCV had a positive impact on the training and testing accuracies of the classifiers.
  • Logistic Regression and SVM achieved the highest training accuracies of 0.98, demonstrating their ability to fit the training data well.
  • Gradient Boosting and Decision Tree achieved the highest testing accuracies of 0.98 and 0.97 respectively, indicating their strong generalization capabilities.
  • The choice of the best classifier should consider both training and testing accuracies and their suitability for the specific task, as well as potential trade-offs between other evaluation metrics such as precision and recall.
